{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa8b0db9-6936-40ee-ba4a-ea13652cc260","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in `CreateMauiApp()` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        events.AddAndroid(android => android\n            .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n            .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n        events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n    });\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated.\n- Each platform helper (`AddAndroid`, `AddiOS`) exposes the native lifecycle callbacks as strongly-typed delegates.\n- Other events are available too — `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnCreate`, etc.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b9ebddf-1a05-45c5-b3b6-7cf8edc012dd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I can answer directly.","outputTokens":382,"requestId":"9BC4:11AB75:620CA9F:6D3B847:69EC0EC7"},"id":"1a9f43af-537d-48db-948c-abfb35e631d1","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:46:07.199Z","parentId":"aa0878e1-8b0d-4603-9a03-3f29872d448d"}
